OpenBSD port: devel/grok-build — ready for doas make install

## Package built

```
/usr/ports/packages/amd64/all/grok-build-0.1.220pl0.tgz  (~61M)
/usr/ports/packages/amd64/ftp/grok-build-0.1.220pl0.tgz  (link)
```

```sh
pkg_info -f -D unsigned /usr/ports/packages/amd64/all/grok-build-0.1.220pl0.tgz
```

## Install (needs root — your step)

```sh
doas pkg_add -D unsigned /usr/ports/packages/amd64/all/grok-build-0.1.220pl0.tgz
# or from the port directory after package exists:
# doas make install
grok --version
```

## How it was packaged (passwordless _pfetch / _pbuild)

```sh
# distfiles already seeded
doas -u _pfetch make fetch

# work tree was rsync'd to /usr/obj/ports from prior user build
doas -u _pbuild make package PKG_CREATE_NO_CHECKS=warn
```

PKG_CREATE_NO_CHECKS=warn: installed sqlite3 is .37.39 while this ports
tree still declares SHARED_LIBS sqlite3 37.38 (package from snapshots is
sqlite3-3.53.2; ports Makefile still 3.53.1 / 37.38). Warning only; package
uses installed sonames.

## Notes

- DESCR must be pure ASCII (UTF-8 em-dash broke pkg_create)
- RUN_DEPENDS textproc/ripgrep
- Binary: bin/grok, ~164M stripped
- Low-memory build defaults in Makefile (not usual for ports; this crate is huge):
  - MAKE_JOBS=1 -> CARGO_BUILD_JOBS=1 (override: make MAKE_JOBS=2)
  - CARGO_PROFILE_RELEASE_CODEGEN_UNITS=1, LTO=thin, DEBUG=0, STRIP=symbols
  - CARGO_INCREMENTAL=0, MODCARGO_RUSTFLAGS=-Ccodegen-units=1
  - DPB_PROPERTIES += lonesome
  - mold/lld linker tweaks skipped (no mold in ports; base ld is fine)

## Runtime: kqueue / fsnotify (2026-07-17)

Symptom under load (script(1) / fixing-grok.log):

```
thread 'notify-rs kqueue loop' panicked at .../kqueue-1.1.1/src/lib.rs:661:86:
called `Option::unwrap()` on a `None` value
```

Cause: notify's BSD backend uses kqueue 1.1.1. When a kevent arrives for an
fd already removed from the watch list (teardown / EMFILE races),
`find_file_ident(...).unwrap()` panics the watcher thread.

Mitigations in this port / openbsd branch:

1. `files/vendor/kqueue` + `[patch.crates-io] kqueue` — skip stale kevents
   instead of unwrap (see vendor/kqueue/OPENBSD-PATCH.md).
2. `xai-fsnotify`: default PerDir strategy on OpenBSD (like Linux), with a
   lower default watch budget (2048) to stay under process open-files limits.
   Override: GROK_FSNOTIFY_PER_DIR, GROK_FSNOTIFY_MAX_WATCHES.

Rebuild the package after these changes; the installed binary still has the
old DWARF paths until reinstalled.
